\subsection{Supplementary checks}
\label{sec:supplementary}

Three supplementary tests are summarized here; full protocols, numerical output, and pre-registration appear in the companion methods note~\cite{Brilliant2026methods}.

\paragraph{Measurement-noise bootstrap.}
A parametric bootstrap of the PDG~2024 charged-lepton masses (four variants: uncorrelated $1\sigma$ baseline, correlated $\rho = 0.5$, tightened $0.5\sigma$, loosened $2\sigma$, $N = 2{,}000$ per variant) places the observed residual $+0.042$~MeV at the $5.5\%$ percentile of the baseline noise distribution. The fraction of bootstrap draws producing a $1\sigma$ hit is $65.7\%$ (B1 baseline), consistent with the Gaussian expectation $\mathrm{erf}(1/\sqrt{2}) \approx 68.3\%$; this is a consistency check confirming that the engine correctly propagates lepton input uncertainties through the Soddy pipeline and the $\msbar$ running. Null~B does not on its own argue against a noise-level explanation.

\paragraph{Comparison family of lepton functions.}
We pre-specified $24$ functions of $(m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau)$ of algebraic complexity comparable to $\mathcal{F}^2$, frozen at the pre-registration commit of~\cite{Brilliant2026methods}. Table~\ref{tab:comparison_family} gives the full list with values on observed leptons. Two of the $24$ fall within $1\sigma$ of $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$: $\mathcal{F}^2$ itself and the algebraic surrogate $(e_1 - \sqrt{p_2})^2$ of~(\ref{eq:F_alg}), which is Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes}'s identity and differs from the first by $0.004$~MeV at present lepton precision. The next-closest miss (row 22) is at $+6.73\sigma$; the remaining 21 variants miss by $\geq 16\sigma$. The same $24$ variants give per-variant random-spectrum hit rates in the narrow range $0$--$0.45\%$ at $N = 2{,}000$ under the A1 prior, indicating that the observed selectivity on $(m_e, m_\mu, m_\tau)$ is not driven by a structural bias of the enumerated family toward small residuals.

